{
  "answer": "**In Charles Comte's *Traité de Législation: VOL I*, Chapter 13 (\"Distinction entre un régime arbitraire et un régime légal. De ce qui constitue la différence\"), this argument appears prominently.[^1][^2]**\n\nComte contends that the distinction between \"arbitrary\" and \"legal\" rule is often overstated or illusory, as a malevolent power can be rendered perfectly regular and codified without becoming benevolent. He illustrates this with the analogy of a slave-master (or proprietor) who imposes a meticulously orderly code on both his human slaves and animal herds—regulating work hours, food rations, punishments, breeding, shearing, slaughter, etc.—creating a \"legal regime\" in form, yet one that delivers no greater liberty or well-being.[^1]\n\nHe reinforces the point earlier by noting that governments (like steam engines with or without regulators) gain uniformity from pre-described laws, but if predatory, this merely systematizes oppression: \"One can put regularity into pillage and into the sharing of booty... there is only more uniformity in the extortions.\"[^2]\n\n[^1]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL I*, [p-9f5b65](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/13/translation/#p-9f5b65/).\n\n[^2]: Charles Comte, *Traité de Législation: VOL I*, [p-5bc401](/works/charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2/13/translation/#p-5bc401/).",
